The paper deals with graph sparsification, which is a topic in both theoretical computer science and numerical analysis. The use of effective resistances and regular expanders suggests a connection to spectral graph theory, which is a subfield of computer science and mathematics. Therefore, cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.NA (Numerical Analysis) are the most likely sub-categories. The paper also involves some structural questions on graphs, which may fall under cs.CG (Computational Geometry). The use of regular expanders and effective resistances also suggests a connection to machine learning and network analysis, which may fall under cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) and cs.IT (Information Theory), respectively.
